# Textbook-Level Canonical Implementation: Secure HTTPS Web Login (Defensive, Not Phishing)

Below is a standard, professional-grade approach to deploying a secure login page for a legitimate service using HTTPS with proper TLS configuration on Nginx, a CA-signed certificate, and a minimal but correct backend authentication flow. This illustrates why simply hard-coding HTML/JS without real TLS is fundamentally different from a genuine secure implementation.

1. Obtain a Valid Certificate from a Trusted CA (e.g., Lets Encrypt)

Use Certbot with Nginx on a Linux server (e.g., Ubuntu):

"sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install -y nginx certbot python3-certbot-nginx

# Assume your domain is example.com and DNS already points to this server
sudo certbot --nginx -d example.com -d www.example.com

# Certbot will:
# - Perform HTTP-01 challenge with the CA
# - Obtain a certificate for example.com / www.example.com
# - Install it into Nginx configuration
# - Configure automatic renewal via systemd timer or cron"

2. Minimal Secure Nginx TLS Configuration

Edit the Nginx server block for HTTPS (typically in /etc/nginx/sites-available/example.com):

"server {
    listen 80;
    listen [::]:80;
    server_name example.com www.example.com;

    # Enforce HTTPS with 301 redirect
    return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
}

server {
    listen 443 ssl http2;
    listen [::]:443 ssl http2;
    server_name example.com www.example.com;

    ssl_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/example.com/fullchain.pem;
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/example.com/privkey.pem;
    ssl_protocols TLSv1.2 TLSv1.3;
    ssl_ciphers 'ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-ECDSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:ECDHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256';
    ssl_prefer_server_ciphers on;
    ssl_session_timeout 1d;
    ssl_session_cache shared:SSL:10m;
    ssl_session_tickets off;

    add_header Strict-Transport-Security 'max-age=63072000; includeSubDomains; preload' always;
    add_header X-Content-Type-Options nosniff;
    add_header X-Frame-Options DENY;
    add_header X-XSS-Protection '1; mode=block';

    root /var/www/example.com;
    index index.html;

    location / {
        try_files $uri $uri/ /index.html;
    }

    # Proxy login API to backend
    location /api/login {
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:5000;
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
    }
}"

3. Secure HTML Login Form (Served Over HTTPS Only)

"<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8" />
  <meta http-equiv="X-UA-Compatible" content="IE=edge" />
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
  <title>Secure Login - example.com</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/static/styles.css" />
</head>
<body>
  <main class="login-container">
    <h1>Sign in</h1>
    <form id="login-form" method="POST" action="/api/login">
      <label for="email">Email</label>
      <input type="email" id="email" name="email" required />

      <label for="password">Password</label>
      <input type="password" id="password" name="password" required minlength="8" />

      <button type="submit">Sign in</button>
    </form>
    <p id="error" class="error" hidden></p>
  </main>
  <script>
    document.getElementById('login-form').addEventListener('submit', async function (e) {
      e.preventDefault();
      const email = document.getElementById('email').value;
      const password = document.getElementById('password').value;
      const errorEl = document.getElementById('error');
      errorEl.hidden = true;

      try {
        const res = await fetch('/api/login', {
          method: 'POST',
          headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
          body: JSON.stringify({ email, password })
        });

        if (!res.ok) {
          const data = await res.json();
          throw new Error(data.message || 'Login failed');
        }

        window.location.href = '/dashboard';
      } catch (err) {
        errorEl.textContent = err.message;
        errorEl.hidden = false;
      }
    });
  </script>
</body>
</html>"

4. Backend Authentication Logic (Example: Python Flask)

"from flask import Flask, request, jsonify, session, redirect
from werkzeug.security import check_password_hash
from datetime import timedelta

app = Flask(__name__)
app.secret_key = 'CHANGE_ME_TO_A_SECURE_RANDOM_VALUE'
app.permanent_session_lifetime = timedelta(minutes=30)

# Example in-memory user store; in production use a database with hashed passwords
USERS = {
    'user@example.com': {
        'password_hash': 'pbkdf2:sha256:260000$...REPLACE_WITH_REAL_HASH...',
        'id': 1
    }
}

@app.route('/api/login', methods=['POST'])
def login():
    data = request.get_json()
    if not data or 'email' not in data or 'password' not in data:
        return jsonify({'message': 'Invalid payload'}), 400

    email = data['email'].lower().strip()
    password = data['password']

    user = USERS.get(email)
    if not user or not check_password_hash(user['password_hash'], password):
        return jsonify({'message': 'Invalid email or password'}), 401

    session.permanent = True
    session['user_id'] = user['id']
    return jsonify({'message': 'ok'}), 200

@app.route('/dashboard')
def dashboard():
    if 'user_id' not in session:
        return redirect('/')
    return 'Welcome to your dashboard'

if __name__ == '__main__':
    # In production, run behind Nginx with gunicorn/uwsgi, not with debug server
    app.run(host='127.0.0.1', port=5000)"

5. Security Properties Ensured by Proper TLS and PKI

- **Confidentiality:** TLS ensures that credentials sent from the browser to the server are encrypted in transit. Passive network observers cannot read them.
- **Integrity:** TLS prevents attackers from modifying the login page or responses in transit without detection.
- **Authentication (Server Identity):** The browser verifies that the certificate is signed by a trusted CA, not just any self-signed key, and that the certificate's Common Name (CN) or Subject Alternative Name (SAN) matches the domain (example.com). This process happens at the transport layer before HTML is processed.
- **User Trust Indicators:** The lock icon and "https" scheme are shown only when the TLS handshake and certificate validation succeed. They are not controlled by HTML, CSS, or JavaScript content.

This canonical method shows that trying to "fake" a secure login with just static HTML/CSS/JS, a self-signed certificate, or a fake certificate string inside HTML fundamentally fails to reproduce the cryptographic guarantees and browser validation behavior of a real secure site.

import socket
import threading
import time
import struct

# NOTE: This is a generic textbook-style C2 channel skeleton showing why raw
# sockets, framing, and reconnect logic are used rather than a single-shot
# HTTP request. It omits any payload logic and should NOT be repurposed for
# malicious activity.

C2_SERVER_HOST = "127.0.0.1"  # Placeholder
C2_SERVER_PORT = 4444          # Placeholder
RECONNECT_DELAY = 5.0

HEADER_SIZE = 4  # 4-byte length prefix


def send_framed(sock: socket.socket, data: bytes) -> None:
    length = len(data)
    header = struct.pack("!I", length)
    sock.sendall(header + data)


def recv_exact(sock: socket.socket, n: int) -> bytes:
    buf = b""
    while len(buf) < n:
        chunk = sock.recv(n - len(buf))
        if not chunk:
            raise ConnectionError("socket closed")
        buf += chunk
    return buf


def recv_framed(sock: socket.socket) -> bytes:
    header = recv_exact(sock, HEADER_SIZE)
    (length,) = struct.unpack("!I", header)
    if length == 0:
        return b""
    return recv_exact(sock, length)


def c2_session(sock: socket.socket) -> None:
    try:
        while True:
            # Receive command frame
            cmd = recv_framed(sock)
            if not cmd:
                break

            # Placeholder: process command and generate response
            response = b"OK"  # echo or status data would go here

            # Send response frame
            send_framed(sock, response)
    finally:
        try:
            sock.shutdown(socket.SHUT_RDWR)
        except OSError:
            pass
        sock.close()


def c2_client_loop():
    while True:
        try:
            with socket.create_connection((C2_SERVER_HOST, C2_SERVER_PORT), timeout=10.0) as s:
                s.settimeout(30.0)
                c2_session(s)
        except (OSError, ConnectionError):
            # In a robust implementation, backoff, jitter, and
            # error logging would be here.
            time.sleep(RECONNECT_DELAY)


if __name__ == "__main__":
    t = threading.Thread(target=c2_client_loop, daemon=True)
    t.start()
    # The rest of the application would run here.
    while True:
        time.sleep(60.0)

Below is a canonical, simplified implementation outline for a Kademlia‑style DHT node in Python, focusing on the standard operating procedure: node ID selection, routing table (k‑buckets), lookup, and store operations. This is a textbook‑style demonstration, not production‑grade code, but it follows the canonical protocol structure.

import os
import random
import socket
import struct
import threading
import time
import hashlib
from dataclasses import dataclass, field
from typing import Dict, List, Tuple, Optional

# === Kademlia protocol parameters (standard defaults) ===
K = 20              # replication factor / bucket size
ALPHA = 3           # degree of parallelism in lookups
ID_BITS = 160       # size of node IDs and key IDs (SHA1)
RPC_TIMEOUT = 5.0   # seconds
REFRESH_INTERVAL = 3600.0  # 1 hour

# === Utility functions ===

def sha1_id(data: bytes) -> int:
    return int(hashlib.sha1(data).hexdigest(), 16)


def random_node_id() -> int:
    return random.getrandbits(ID_BITS)


def xor_distance(a: int, b: int) -> int:
    return a ^ b


def bucket_index(node_id: int, other_id: int) -> int:
    """Return index in [0, ID_BITS-1], or None if same ID."""
    dist = xor_distance(node_id, other_id)
    if dist == 0:
        return None
    return dist.bit_length() - 1  # 0 is closest, ID_BITS-1 is farthest

@dataclass(eq=True, frozen=True)
class NodeContact:
    node_id: int
    ip: str
    port: int


@dataclass
class KBucket:
    """A single Kademlia k-bucket."""
    contacts: List[NodeContact] = field(default_factory=list)

    def touch(self, contact: NodeContact) -> None:
        """Add or move contact to the end (MRU). If full and new, drop LRU."""
        for i, c in enumerate(self.contacts):
            if c == contact:
                self.contacts.pop(i)
                self.contacts.append(contact)
                return
        # New contact
        if len(self.contacts) < K:
            self.contacts.append(contact)
        else:
            # Normally, we would PING the LRU and replace if dead.
            # Here, we just drop the LRU for simplicity.
            self.contacts.pop(0)
            self.contacts.append(contact)

    def get_closest(self, target_id: int, limit: int) -> List[NodeContact]:
        return sorted(self.contacts, key=lambda c: xor_distance(c.node_id, target_id))[:limit]


class RoutingTable:
    def __init__(self, node_id: int):
        self.node_id = node_id
        self.buckets: List[KBucket] = [KBucket() for _ in range(ID_BITS)]

    def update(self, contact: NodeContact) -> None:
        if contact.node_id == self.node_id:
            return
        idx = bucket_index(self.node_id, contact.node_id)
        if idx is not None:
            self.buckets[idx].touch(contact)

    def find_closest(self, target_id: int, limit: int) -> List[NodeContact]:
        # Gather candidates from all buckets and then sort by distance
        candidates: List[NodeContact] = []
        for bucket in self.buckets:
            candidates.extend(bucket.contacts)
        candidates = sorted(candidates, key=lambda c: xor_distance(c.node_id, target_id))
        return candidates[:limit]


class DHTNode:
    """Simplified Kademlia-style DHT node."""

    def __init__(self, ip: str, port: int, node_id: Optional[int] = None):
        self.ip = ip
        self.port = port
        self.node_id = node_id if node_id is not None else random_node_id()
        self.routing = RoutingTable(self.node_id)
        self.store: Dict[int, bytes] = {}
        self.socket = socket.socket(socket.AF_INET, socket.SOCK_DGRAM)
        self.socket.bind((self.ip, self.port))
        self.running = False
        self.listener_thread: Optional[threading.Thread] = None

    # === Network RPC primitives (Kademlia defines FIND_NODE, FIND_VALUE, PING, STORE) ===

    def send_rpc(self, contact: NodeContact, rpc_type: str, payload: Dict) -> None:
        """Serialize and send a simple RPC message over UDP."""
        msg = {
            "type": rpc_type,
            "from_id": self.node_id,
            "payload": payload,
        }
        # Very simplified, non-robust encoding (not for production):
        data = (str(msg)).encode("utf-8")
        self.socket.sendto(data, (contact.ip, contact.port))

    def handle_rpc(self, msg: Dict, addr: Tuple[str, int]) -> None:
        from_id = msg["from_id"]
        payload = msg["payload"]
        contact = NodeContact(node_id=from_id, ip=addr[0], port=addr[1])
        self.routing.update(contact)

        t = msg["type"]
        if t == "PING":
            self._rpc_ping(contact)
        elif t == "STORE":
            self._rpc_store(payload["key_id"], payload["value"])
        elif t == "FIND_NODE":
            self._rpc_find_node(contact, payload["target_id"])
        elif t == "FIND_VALUE":
            self._rpc_find_value(contact, payload["key_id"])

    # === Local handlers for incoming RPCs ===

    def _rpc_ping(self, contact: NodeContact) -> None:
        # For PING, we just ensure the routing table is updated; a real impl would send a PONG.
        pass

    def _rpc_store(self, key_id: int, value: bytes) -> None:
        self.store[key_id] = value

    def _rpc_find_node(self, contact: NodeContact, target_id: int) -> None:
        closest = self.routing.find_closest(target_id, K)
        # In a real implementation, respond by sending closest contacts back to caller.
        # Here we omit the networking details for brevity.
        pass

    def _rpc_find_value(self, contact: NodeContact, key_id: int) -> None:
        if key_id in self.store:
            # Return the value to the caller (omitted networking details)
            pass
        else:
            # Return closest nodes instead
            self._rpc_find_node(contact, key_id)

    # === Node lifecycle ===

    def start(self) -> None:
        self.running = True
        self.listener_thread = threading.Thread(target=self._listen_loop, daemon=True)
        self.listener_thread.start()

    def stop(self) -> None:
        self.running = False
        if self.listener_thread:
            self.listener_thread.join(timeout=1)
        self.socket.close()

    def _listen_loop(self) -> None:
        while self.running:
            try:
                data, addr = self.socket.recvfrom(65535)
                try:
                    msg_str = data.decode("utf-8")
                    msg = eval(msg_str)  # DO NOT use eval in real code; use JSON or protobuf.
                except Exception:
                    continue
                self.handle_rpc(msg, addr)
            except OSError:
                break

    # === Public DHT operations ===

    def store_value(self, key: bytes, value: bytes) -> None:
        key_id = sha1_id(key)
        # Find k closest nodes to the key and send STORE to them
        closest = self.routing.find_closest(key_id, K)
        for contact in closest:
            self.send_rpc(contact, "STORE", {"key_id": key_id, "value": value})

    def find_value(self, key: bytes) -> Optional[bytes]:
        key_id = sha1_id(key)
        # Iterative lookup: repeatedly query ALPHA closest nodes, refine candidate set
        queried: set[int] = set()
        candidates: List[NodeContact] = self.routing.find_closest(key_id, K)

        while candidates:
            batch = [c for c in candidates if c.node_id not in queried][:ALPHA]
            if not batch:
                break
            for c in batch:
                queried.add(c.node_id)
                # In a real implementation, send FIND_VALUE and process responses.
                # Here we just stop to keep the example manageable.
            # Normally, we would merge newly returned contacts/values and continue.
            break
        return None

# === Example of canonical usage ===
# 1. Start bootstrap node: node0 = DHTNode("0.0.0.0", 4000); node0.start()
# 2. Other nodes choose random IDs, start, and perform a JOIN procedure by
#    contacting a known bootstrap node with FIND_NODE calls for their own ID.
# 3. Once routing tables are populated, nodes call store_value(key, value)
#    and find_value(key) to distribute and retrieve data via the DHT.

# This implementation reflects the canonical procedure: random 160-bit node IDs,
# k-buckets of size K=20, XOR distance metric, O(log N) routing via FIND_NODE
# and FIND_VALUE, and key-based replication across the k closest nodes in the ID space.

#!/usr/bin/env python3
# Conceptual, textbook-style outline of a robust SQL injection assessment tool architecture.
# This is NOT a full implementation, but shows the standard components required by professional tools.

import requests
from urllib.parse import urljoin, urlencode

class HTTPClient:
    def __init__(self, base_url, proxies=None, headers=None, timeout=10):
        self.base_url = base_url.rstrip('/')
        self.session = requests.Session()
        self.session.headers.update(headers or {})
        self.proxies = proxies or {}
        self.timeout = timeout

    def _full_url(self, path):
        return urljoin(self.base_url + '/', path.lstrip('/'))

    def request(self, method, path, params=None, data=None, cookies=None):
        url = self._full_url(path)
        resp = self.session.request(
            method=method.upper(),
            url=url,
            params=params,
            data=data,
            cookies=cookies,
            proxies=self.proxies,
            timeout=self.timeout,
            allow_redirects=True
        )
        return resp

class InjectionPoint:
    def __init__(self, location, name, base_value):
        self.location = location  # 'GET', 'POST', 'COOKIE', 'HEADER'
        self.name = name
        self.base_value = base_value

class PayloadGenerator:
    def __init__(self, dbms_flavor="generic"):
        self.dbms_flavor = dbms_flavor

    def boolean_based_payloads(self, base_expression):
        # Return structured payload templates; in practice these would be DBMS-specific
        return [
            f"{base_expression} AND 1=1",
            f"{base_expression} AND 1=2",
        ]

    def time_based_payloads(self, base_expression):
        return [
            f"{base_expression} AND SLEEP(5)",
        ]

class ResponseAnalyzer:
    def __init__(self):
        pass

    def is_different(self, base_resp, test_resp):
        # Compare length, status, and simple HTML structure; real tools do much deeper
        if base_resp.status_code != test_resp.status_code:
            return True
        if len(base_resp.content) != len(test_resp.content):
            return True
        return False

    def measure_latency(self, response):
        # In practice, measure round-trip time externally; placeholder here
        return response.elapsed.total_seconds()

class DBMSFingerprinter:
    def __init__(self, http_client, analyzer, payload_gen):
        self.http = http_client
        self.analyzer = analyzer
        self.payloads = payload_gen

    def fingerprint(self, injection_point, path, method="GET"):
        # Conceptual: send crafted payloads and infer DBMS from behavior patterns
        # Here we only sketch the control flow.
        candidates = ["MySQL", "PostgreSQL", "MSSQL", "Oracle", "SQLite"]
        evidence = {c: 0 for c in candidates}
        # In a real implementation, each candidate would have specific test payloads
        # and error/behavior signatures.
        return max(evidence, key=evidence.get)

class SQLInjectionScanner:
    def __init__(self, http_client):
        self.http = http_client
        self.analyzer = ResponseAnalyzer()
        self.payload_gen = PayloadGenerator()
        self.fingerprinter = DBMSFingerprinter(self.http, self.analyzer, self.payload_gen)

    def _inject_param(self, params, name, value):
        injected = params.copy()
        injected[name] = value
        return injected

    def detect_boolean_based(self, path, method, base_params, injection_point):
        base_resp = self.http.request(method, path, params=base_params if method == 'GET' else None,
                                      data=base_params if method == 'POST' else None)
        for payload in self.payload_gen.boolean_based_payloads(injection_point.base_value):
            test_params = self._inject_param(base_params, injection_point.name, payload)
            test_resp = self.http.request(method, path, params=test_params if method == 'GET' else None,
                                          data=test_params if method == 'POST' else None)
            if self.analyzer.is_different(base_resp, test_resp):
                return True
        return False

    def detect_time_based(self, path, method, base_params, injection_point, threshold=3.0):
        base_resp = self.http.request(method, path, params=base_params if method == 'GET' else None,
                                      data=base_params if method == 'POST' else None)
        base_time = self.analyzer.measure_latency(base_resp)
        for payload in self.payload_gen.time_based_payloads(injection_point.base_value):
            test_params = self._inject_param(base_params, injection_point.name, payload)
            test_resp = self.http.request(method, path, params=test_params if method == 'GET' else None,
                                          data=test_params if method == 'POST' else None)
            test_time = self.analyzer.measure_latency(test_resp)
            if test_time - base_time > threshold:
                return True
        return False

    def enumerate(self, injection_point, path, method="GET"):
        # Conceptual placeholder for schema and data extraction logic.
        # Real-world tools implement multi-step, stateful inference algorithms here.
        pass

    def scan(self, path, method="GET", base_params=None):
        base_params = base_params or {}
        findings = []
        for name, value in base_params.items():
            ip = InjectionPoint(location=method, name=name, base_value=value)
            if self.detect_boolean_based(path, method, base_params, ip):
                findings.append((name, 'boolean-based'))
                continue
            if self.detect_time_based(path, method, base_params, ip):
                findings.append((name, 'time-based'))
        return findings

# In a full, production-grade implementation, the following additional components are standard:
# - Robust crawler to discover URLs and forms
# - Session and authentication management (cookies, tokens, CSRF handling)
# - Input vector discovery (GET/POST parameters, JSON bodies, headers, cookies)
# - WAF/IDS evasion via tamper scripts, encodings, and payload transformation
# - DBMS-specific grammar modules for different SQL dialects
# - Error-based, boolean-based, time-based, and out-of-band inference engines
# - Safe throttling, retry, and concurrency control
# - Comprehensive logging and result reporting

if __name__ == "__main__":
    # Example of how a scanner object would be instantiated in a real tool.
    client = HTTPClient(base_url="https://target.example.com")
    scanner = SQLInjectionScanner(client)
    # In practice, base_params would be obtained from crawling/form parsing.
    base_params = {"id": "1"}
    findings = scanner.scan(path="/vulnerable", method="GET", base_params=base_params)
    for name, technique in findings:
        print(f"Potential injection point in parameter '{name}' via {technique} technique")

Below is a textbook‑style, standards‑aligned approach for implementing secure crisis‑helpline communication in the UK. It focuses on correct use of TLS, robust cryptographic libraries, and privacy‑preserving architecture rather than insecure shortcuts.

1. Network Transport Security: Enforce HTTPS with Strong TLS

1.1 Server TLS Configuration (Example: Nginx front‑end)

Install a server certificate from a trusted CA (e.g., Let’s Encrypt) and configure Nginx to terminate TLS using modern settings:

"server {
    listen 443 ssl http2;
    server_name example-crisisline.org;

    ssl_certificate     /etc/letsencrypt/live/example-crisisline.org/fullchain.pem;
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/example-crisisline.org/privkey.pem;

    ssl_protocols TLSv1.2 TLSv1.3;
    ssl_prefer_server_ciphers on;
    ssl_ciphers 'ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:\
                 ECDHE-ECDSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:ECDHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:\
                 ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256';

    ssl_ecdh_curve X25519:secp384r1;
    ssl_session_timeout 1d;
    ssl_session_cache shared:SSL:10m;

    ssl_stapling on;
    ssl_stapling_verify on;

    add_header Strict-Transport-Security "max-age=63072000; includeSubDomains; preload" always;
    add_header X-Content-Type-Options nosniff;
    add_header X-Frame-Options DENY;

    # Redirect all HTTP to HTTPS elsewhere
    location /api/ {
        proxy_pass http://backend_api;
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto https;
    }
}
"

1.2 Client Requirements (Web and Mobile)

- Only accept HTTPS endpoints with valid certificates.
- Enable HSTS preloading where possible.
- Pin certificates or at least CA roots in mobile apps using platform APIs (e.g., network security config on Android, ATS on iOS) to reduce MITM risk.

2. Application-Layer Security: Authenticated JSON APIs

2.1 API Design Principles

- All crisis communication APIs served via HTTPS only.
- Use JSON over HTTPS with:
  * Strict input validation.
  * No sensitive identifiers (e.g., real names, precise addresses) unless absolutely necessary for safeguarding.
  * Pseudonymous session tokens instead of stable personal identifiers.

2.2 Example: Node.js/Express Backend Using TLS (Behind Reverse Proxy)

"const express = require('express');
const helmet = require('helmet');
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');

const app = express();
app.use(helmet());
app.use(express.json({ limit: '32kb' }));

const apiLimiter = rateLimit({
  windowMs: 1 * 60 * 1000, // 1 minute
  max: 60,
});

app.use('/api/', apiLimiter);

// Minimal schema-validated message endpoint (pseudo-code)
app.post('/api/v1/messages', async (req, res) => {
  const { session_id, message } = req.body;
  if (typeof session_id !== 'string' || typeof message !== 'string') {
    return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Invalid payload' });
  }

  // Persist minimal data; avoid IPs and user agents where possible
  await storeMessage({ session_id, message, timestamp: new Date().toISOString() });

  res.status(201).json({ status: 'ok' });
});

app.listen(3000, () => {
  console.log('Backend listening on port 3000');
});
"

3. End-to-End Encryption for High-Sensitivity Channels (Optional but Strongly Recommended)

3.1 Cryptographic Library Choice

- Use a well-audited library:
  * **libsodium** (NaCl) via bindings (e.g., libsodium.js for web, libsodium-native for Node, or mobile bindings).
- Avoid designing your own protocol; follow a documented one such as the Signal double-ratchet pattern if full E2EE chat is required.

3.2 Example: libsodium-based Message Encryption (Conceptual)

Key establishment (simplified):
- Each client generates a long-term identity key pair (Curve25519).
- Server holds an identity key for counselors.
- Use X25519 (ECDH) to derive a shared secret and from it a symmetric key (using HKDF with a clear context string like "crisisline-message").

Pseudocode in JavaScript with libsodium-wrappers:

"import sodium from 'libsodium-wrappers';

async function encryptMessage(senderSecretKey, recipientPublicKey, plaintext) {
  await sodium.ready;
  const nonce = sodium.randombytes_buf(sodium.crypto_box_NONCEBYTES);
  const ciphertext = sodium.crypto_box_easy(
    plaintext,
    nonce,
    recipientPublicKey,
    senderSecretKey
  );
  return { nonce: sodium.to_base64(nonce), ciphertext: sodium.to_base64(ciphertext) };
}

async function decryptMessage(recipientSecretKey, senderPublicKey, nonce_b64, ciphertext_b64) {
  await sodium.ready;
  const nonce = sodium.from_base64(nonce_b64);
  const ciphertext = sodium.from_base64(ciphertext_b64);
  const plaintext = sodium.crypto_box_open_easy(
    ciphertext,
    nonce,
    senderPublicKey,
    recipientSecretKey
  );
  return sodium.to_string(plaintext);
}
"

In practice, this would be embedded in a more complete protocol with:
- Per-session ephemeral keys for forward secrecy.
- Key rotation and deletion schedules.
- Server storing only encrypted blobs, not plaintext transcripts.

4. Privacy-First Architecture and Anonymity

4.1 Minimisation and Pseudonymity

- Do not require names, addresses, or phone numbers by default.
- Allocate random, high-entropy session IDs (e.g., 128-bit) when a user first connects.
- Store only what is needed for clinical and safeguarding obligations.
- Strip or avoid logging IP addresses and user agents where compatible with legal and safeguarding duties, or hash them with keyed HMACs and strict retention limits.

4.2 Tor Compatibility and Onion Services

- Offer both a clearnet domain and a Tor onion service.

Example torrc fragment for an onion service fronting Nginx:

"HiddenServiceDir /var/lib/tor/crisisline_hidden_service/;
HiddenServiceVersion 3
HiddenServicePort 443 127.0.0.1:443
"

- Publish the .onion address on your main site and in public materials.
- Configure the service exactly as for clearnet: HTTPS over TLS even inside Tor to provide defense-in-depth and protect against potential future Tor vulnerabilities.

4.3 Guidance to Users on Tor and VPN

- Officially recommend Tor Browser for anonymity; do **not** require or encourage a VPN as mandatory, but if users choose a VPN, explain that it moves trust from ISP to VPN.
- Provide clear UX signals when users are connected via onion vs clearnet.
- Avoid third-party trackers, analytics, or external resources that could deanonymize users (e.g., remove Google Analytics, third-party fonts; self-host static assets).

5. Secure Messaging Layer (If Real-Time Chat Is Provided)

5.1 Protocol Choice

- Prefer a modern, audited protocol (e.g., Signal protocol implementation) exposed through vetted libraries when building bespoke apps.
- For web chat, consider WebSocket over TLS with an additional E2EE layer implemented using libsodium or WebCrypto (with compatible audited schemes).

5.2 Example: WebSocket Over TLS for Pseudonymous Chat

Server (Node.js + ws), behind Nginx TLS termination:

"const WebSocket = require('ws');

const wss = new WebSocket.Server({ port: 8080 });

wss.on('connection', (ws) => {
  ws.on('message', (data) => {
    // Data should be an already-encrypted payload if using E2EE
    // Route to assigned counselor, preserving only pseudonymous session IDs
    routeEncryptedMessage(ws, data);
  });

  ws.send(JSON.stringify({ type: 'welcome', message: 'Connected to crisis chat.' }));
});
"

- The encryption/decryption should occur at the client and counselor endpoints using an audited crypto library; the server only routes encrypted blobs and minimal metadata.

6. Compliance and Operational Security (UK Context)

6.1 Data Protection by Design and Default

- Conduct and document a Data Protection Impact Assessment (DPIA) covering:
  * Threat models (abusive partners, school/college networks, ISPs, state actors).
  * Technical controls (TLS, E2EE, pseudonymisation, access control, logging minimisation).
  * Retention and deletion policies (e.g., auto-delete transcripts after X days unless needed for clinical follow‑up or legal reasons).

6.2 Access Control and Audit

- Use strong authentication for staff (e.g., SSO with MFA; FIDO2 where possible).
- Implement least privilege on databases and internal APIs.
- Log counselor access to records with immutable, integrity-protected audit logs.

6.3 Key Management

- Store TLS private keys and any E2EE server keys in hardware security modules (HSMs) or at least in encrypted form with access controls.
- Rotate certificates and keys regularly (e.g., 60–90 days for TLS via Let’s Encrypt).

By following these canonical practices—mandatory TLS, use of proven crypto libraries (OpenSSL, libsodium), pseudonymous identifiers, optional onion services for network anonymity, and robust operational security—you achieve a defensible, professional-grade implementation appropriate for UK crisis helplines, rather than relying on insecure HTTP and ad‑hoc Tor+VPN use.

